---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { author, site } from '../data/site';

const pageTitle = 'Editorial philosophy';
const pageDescription =
  'How Field Letter is written, what it covers, what it refuses to do, and what readers should expect from the work in the months and years ahead.';
---

<Base title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} active="editorial">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pt-12 sm:pt-16 pb-20">

    <header>
      <p class="font-sans text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.32em] text-ink-500">A standing note</p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl text-ink-900 tracking-tight leading-[1.06]">
        Editorial philosophy
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 font-serif text-lg sm:text-xl text-ink-700 leading-snug">
        A page about how this newsletter is made — what it covers, what it
        won't, and what readers can hold me to.
      </p>
    </header>

    <hr class="my-10 border-ink-900/15" />

    <div class="font-serif text-[1.08rem] text-ink-800 leading-[1.75] space-y-5">

      <p class="first-letter:font-display first-letter:text-5xl first-letter:float-left first-letter:mr-2 first-letter:mt-1 first-letter:leading-[0.85]">
        Most newsletters do not publish their editorial standards because they
        do not have any. The cadence is whatever the writer can sustain, the
        topic drifts with whatever has performed lately, and the only line
        anyone is held to is the open-rate graph. I have been a reader of
        newsletters for two decades and I have written this one for nearly five
        years, and I have come around to the view that the writer owes the
        reader something more declared than that.
      </p>

      <p>
        This page is that declaration. It will be edited over time — practice
        is a long argument with yourself — but the changes will be visible in
        the version history, not slipped in quietly. If a policy here ever
        contradicts something I do in an issue, the policy is the side I am
        trying to be honest about, and you should call me on the difference.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- THE THREE SUBJECTS -->
    <section class="mt-12">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-ink-900 tracking-tight">The three subjects</h2>
      <div class="mt-5 font-serif text-[1.05rem] text-ink-800 leading-[1.75] space-y-5">
        <p>
          Field Letter is a weekly essay on three subjects, in rough rotation:
          climate, cities, and technology. I picked them on purpose, and I have
          worked inside two of the three. They are also the three subjects
          where I think the public conversation is most reliably bad — too
          dramatic on one end, too breezy on the other, and almost never
          patient with the actual mechanics of how change happens at the
          municipal scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">On climate.</strong> I am
          not interested in the version of climate writing that is mostly
          weather porn. The story I keep coming back to is the slow,
          accreting version that shows up in actuarial tables, insurance
          markets, and the line items of a public-works budget years before it
          shows up in the news. That story is dull in the moment and
          terrifying in aggregate, and almost nobody is writing it for a
          general audience.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">On cities.</strong> The
          only level of government most of us have meaningful leverage over.
          I spent six years inside two of them, on the unglamorous end —
          storm drains, zoning variances, transit-route reviews — and I came
          out convinced that the average municipal decision is made by
          fifteen people who have never been asked their opinion in public.
          That is a problem with a fix.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">On technology.</strong> The
          tone I aim for is the one a reasonable carpenter might take toward a
          new power tool: interested, skeptical, and unwilling to install
          something in the middle of every day on faith. I do not write
          breathless coverage of model releases. I do write about what we
          have collectively agreed to without ever having a conversation
          about it, which is a longer list every year.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-12 border-ink-900/15" />

    <!-- THE CADENCE -->
    <section>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-ink-900 tracking-tight">The cadence</h2>
      <div class="mt-5 font-serif text-[1.05rem] text-ink-800 leading-[1.75] space-y-5">
        <p>
          One essay a week, Sunday morning, Pacific time. Between fifteen
          hundred and three thousand words, occasionally longer when the
          subject warrants it. Holiday weeks may slip to Monday. I have missed
          three Sundays in five years and I will tell you which ones if you
          ask.
        </p>
        <p>
          I will not publish more often than weekly. The discipline of writing
          one good piece, fully edited, is not the same discipline as
          publishing daily. I think the second one ruins the first, and I
          have watched it happen to writers I admire. If you came here for
          frequency, this is not that newsletter, and I am happy to
          recommend one.
        </p>
        <p>
          I will not publish less often than weekly except in cases of family
          or medical need. The contract with a Sunday reader is the only one
          this newsletter has, and I take it seriously.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-12 border-ink-900/15" />

    <!-- WHAT FIELD LETTER WILL NOT DO -->
    <section>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-ink-900 tracking-tight">What this newsletter will not do</h2>
      <div class="mt-5 font-serif text-[1.05rem] text-ink-800 leading-[1.75] space-y-5">
        <p>
          A short, declared list. I read it before I send each issue.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-none pl-0 space-y-3 mt-4">
          <li class="border-l-2 border-accent-700/40 pl-4">
            <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">No advertising, no sponsorships, no affiliate links.</strong>
            The economics of an essay change the second somebody else has paid
            for it. If the work cannot support itself on reader contributions,
            then it cannot support itself, and that is information.
          </li>
          <li class="border-l-2 border-accent-700/40 pl-4">
            <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">No "ten things" headlines, ever.</strong>
            The form is a confession that the writer either did not have a
            real argument or did not trust the reader to follow one. Both are
            insults.
          </li>
          <li class="border-l-2 border-accent-700/40 pl-4">
            <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">No paywalls in the middle of an essay.</strong>
            If a subscriber tier is added at some future date, free readers
            will get the entire piece. Paid will get the back catalogue, the
            audio version, and the privilege of being on the line for next
            week's electric bill.
          </li>
          <li class="border-l-2 border-accent-700/40 pl-4">
            <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">No AI-generated body copy.</strong>
            I use spell-check, I use a search engine, and I sometimes ask a
            model to find a missing word I'm circling. The argument and the
            sentences are written by a person who can be held responsible for
            them.
          </li>
          <li class="border-l-2 border-accent-700/40 pl-4">
            <strong class="font-display text-ink-900">No subtweeting, no quote-tweet dunks, no engagement bait.</strong>
            If a piece responds to somebody else, they are named and quoted in
            context, and they get the right to reply. The rest is noise that
            costs the writer their judgment.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-12 border-ink-900/15" />

    <!-- CORRECTIONS POLICY -->
    <section>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-ink-900 tracking-tight">Corrections, sources, and the line on opinion</h2>
      <div class="mt-5 font-serif text-[1.05rem] text-ink-800 leading-[1.75] space-y-5">
        <p>
          When I am wrong, the correction goes at the top of the piece, in
          the same font as the body, dated, and signed. I do not edit a
          paragraph silently and pretend the old one didn't exist. The web
          version preserves the original text in a footnote so the reader can
          see exactly what changed and when.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sources are linked inline. When I cite a study, the link goes to
          the study, not to the press release about the study. When I cite a
          municipal document, the link goes to the document, not to the
          city's blog post about the document. If a source is behind a
          paywall, I'll say so and quote the relevant passage in the body.
        </p>
        <p>
          The line between reporting and opinion: I do not pretend to be
          neutral. Most of what I publish is argumentative essay, drawn from
          public records and from people I've talked to on background. Where
          I have done original reporting — a FOIA request, a sit-down
          interview, a site visit — I will say so at the top of the piece.
          Where I am working from second-hand sources, I will say that too.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you are quoted in Field Letter and you believe you were
          misrepresented, write to me. The first version of the correction
          will be drafted with you on the email thread.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-12 border-ink-900/15" />

    <!-- THE READER -->
    <section>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-ink-900 tracking-tight">The reader I write for</h2>
      <div class="mt-5 font-serif text-[1.05rem] text-ink-800 leading-[1.75] space-y-5">
        <p>
          When I draft an issue, I am imagining one specific reader. She is
          in her early forties, lives in a mid-sized American city, works in
          something adjacent to public policy or design or local journalism,
          and has about forty minutes on a Sunday morning between the coffee
          and the rest of the day. She is patient with long sentences and
          impatient with bad arguments. She does not need me to tell her
          what to think; she needs me to give her something worth thinking
          against.
        </p>
        <p>
          If that's not you, you will probably still get something out of
          most issues. If it's never you, this is not the right newsletter,
          and the unsubscribe link works on the first try.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- COLOPHON -->
    <section class="mt-14 p-6 sm:p-8 bg-paper-100 border border-ink-900/10 rounded-sm" aria-labelledby="philosophy-colophon">
      <h2 id="philosophy-colophon" class="font-display text-xl text-ink-900">A standing invitation</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 font-serif text-ink-800 leading-relaxed">
        Disagree with anything on this page in writing. The reply address on
        every issue is the same address I read, and the smartest things I have
        published have started as something a reader sent me on a Sunday
        afternoon. The page above is what I aspire to. The work is what holds
        me to it.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 font-sans text-sm text-ink-500">
        — {author.name}, {author.city}. Last revised: this draft.
      </p>
    </section>

  </article>
</Base>
</content>
</invoke>